item.title: U.S. Makes Diplomatic Push for Taiwan to Attend WHO Summit
item.description: A fight over whether Taiwan can participate in a World Health Organization conference on the coronavirus pandemic later this month is escalating a bitter tug of war between the U.S. and China over leadership within the U.N. system.

item.title: American Says Failed Venezuelan Invasion Was to Arrest Maduro
item.description: Luke Alexander Denman, an American, was hired to lead a ragtag group of insurgents to seize the Caracas airport, overthrow President Nicolás Maduro and fly him to the U.S., the imprisoned Iraq war veteran explained in a video.

item.title: Iraq Gets New Government After Months of Political Deadlock
item.description: Iraq swore in a new government after months of political deadlock that has hampered the country’s ability to respond to multiple crises exacerbated by the coronavirus pandemic.

item.title: Israel's High Court Clears Way for Netanyahu to Form Next Government
item.description: Israel’s top court ruled that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu can form a government while under indictment, removing a final hurdle in his bid to remain in power as he goes on trial later this month on corruption charges.

item.title: Coronavirus Casts Deep Chill Over U.S.-China Relations
item.description: The pandemic has brought relations between the two to a modern-day nadir as they try to outmaneuver one another to shape the world order.

item.title: How Germany Kept Its Factories Open During the Pandemic
item.description: Strict safety rules, testing and contact tracing enabled the country to do something that has eluded most other major developed economies: keep manufacturing running without suffering major outbreaks.
